William Blair Private Wealth Management Consulting Services will provide periodic updates on market activity when significant shifts in the market occur. Your William Blair wealth advisor is committed to helping you and your family through all market conditions.
  • Stocks fell today as the financial sector faced increased pressure. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 0.9%, while the S&P 500 fell by 0.7%. The Nasdaq Composite was flat for the day. European equities were down nearly 3.5% as represented by the Euro Stoxx 50.
  • While U.S. markets appeared to stabilize on Tuesday following Silicon Valley Bank’s and Signature Bank’s collapses, attention turned to larger banks today. Credit Suisse hit an all-time low after Saudi National Bank, the bank’s largest investor, stated that it could not provide further funding. Earlier this week, Credit Suisse announced that it had found material weaknesses in its internal control over financial reporting for the years 2021 and 2022.
  • Equity markets partially rebounded off the session’s lows late in the day as the Swiss National Bank issued a statement saying that Credit Suisse “meets the capital and liquidity requirements imposed on systemically important banks.” It further noted that, if necessary, the SNB will provide Credit Suisse with liquidity.
  • With investors flocking to safety and reduced expectations of a Federal Reserve interest rate hike at next week’s FOMC meeting, Treasury yields fell sharply. The 2-year Treasury yield, which is closely tied to Fed policy, dropped as low as 3.68% before returning to levels near 4%.
  • Two new economic data points were published today, both of which may give the Fed additional cover to consider a pause at next week’s FOMC meeting. The Producer Price Index (PPI) fell 0.1% for the month, versus an estimated 0.3% increase, and February retail sales pulled back 0.4%, versus consensus for a 0.1% decline.
  • As markets continue to experience higher-than-average volatility, we encourage you to maintain a disciplined investment approach that considers your time horizon, risk tolerance, return goals, and liquidity needs.
Our clients are our highest priority. It is always important to keep open lines of communication, especially during turbulent times. Please contact your William Blair wealth advisor with questions or to discuss your individual circumstances.
